<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06171173 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06171173 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Lynn Magnoli  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  LOS-GATOS; RESTAURANT; PROFESSIONAL; RECIPE; PROFILE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Profession: Owner and founder, Icing on the Cake, 223 N. Santa Cruz Ave., LosGatos.;    Background: Born and raised in San Jose. Began college but left togo into business in the ski industry. By age 25, she had saved enough money toopen Icing on the Cake in September 1985. She did it on a shoestring, withouta bank loan and without formal training in either business or the foodindustry. Icing on the Cake makes wedding and special-occasion cakes, as wellas muffins, 12 types of cookies every day and other goodies. It started withone employee -- Magnoli. She got help now and then from a friend, and hermother, Patti Magnoli-Dodd, whom she credits with giving her a talent forworking with decadent ingredients. She now employs 12 people. Magnoli alwaysknew she wanted to own a bakery. &quot;I remember baking little cakes inkindergarten,&quot; she says. She and her mom also started a company next doorcalled Hamperstamps, which specializes in ink pads and rubber stamps.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Food  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  LYNN MAGNOLI  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  ConnoisseurFour-StarFAVORITES OF CELEBRITY GOURMETS  </MEMO><TEXT>     Her most popular cake flavors: Chocolate buttermilk and carrot.;    Styleof cooking: Homemade, &quot;honest-to-goodness homemade desserts, no preservatives,all the best stuff.&quot;;    Her typical day: Begins at 7:30 a.m. and goes untilabout 5:30 p.m., but in the early days of the company, she worked seven-dayweeks, 15 hours a day.;    Marital status: Single, but attached.;    Age: 31.;   Home: Campbell.;    Relaxation: Going to the beach, aerobics, bicycling andtennis.;    Favorite restaurant: Il Fornaio, Palo Alto.;    Favorite book:&quot;The Thorn Birds&quot; by Colleen McCullough.;    Musical preference: Jazz.;   Car: Five-year-old Honda wagon.;    Hero: My mother.;    Proudest moment:Opening the bakery. &quot;Achieving success, knowing that I put all my effort intoit and followed through. Putting myself on the line, taking a big risk,cutting off my income completely to follow a little dream.&quot;;    Funniest thingthat happened to one of her cakes: A dog sneaked into a room at a wedding andate off the top layer right before the reception.;    If you could have onelast meal, it would be: Anything chocolate, dark and bittersweet.;    Describeyourself: &quot;Intense, with a great sense of humor. I love life and I love whatI'm doing.&quot;;    Favorite recipe, aside from the goodies she sells:;   GARLICPOTATOES GRATIN;  3; pounds red potatoes, peeled and sliced;  1 1/2  cupsgrated Gruyere cheese;  4; cloves garlic, minced;  3; tablespoons butter;  2;cups heavy cream;  1; teaspoon salt;  1/2; teaspoon black pepper;   Layer halfof the potatoes and half of the cheese in an ungreased 13-by-9-by-2-inchbaking dish. Top with remaining potatoes. Saute garlic in butter in a smallskillet until golden brown. Pour over casserole. Combine cream, salt andpepper. Mix well. Pour over casserole. Sprinkle with remaining cheese. Bake at325 degrees for 75 minutes. Serves 8.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910619  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  6C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  482  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday June 19, 199100171173,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>